{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 Petitioner pharmaceutical company filed for writ of error from a judgment which allowed respondent parents to recover for a claim based upon petitioner's drug, which allegedly caused a birth defect in respondents' baby. Petitioner asserted that respondents failed to provide sufficient evidence that the drug caused the baby to be born with a birth defect. On review, the court focused on causation and examined the record regarding the question of scientific reliability. The court found that isolated studies and expert opinions finding a statistically significant association between the drug at issue and birth defects would not be legally sufficient evidence of causation. The court surmised that properly designed and executed studies could be part of the evidence supporting causation in a toxic tort case such as in the case of a pharmaceutical drug. However, respondents attempted to prove causation primarily through expert testimony based on epidemiological and animal studies. The court found that this was not scientifically reliable evidence and was not sufficient to support the verdict. The judgment was reversed accordingly.}
